\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Will AI substitute for or complement workers?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Will it raise or reduce wages?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Will it upskill or deskill workers?
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Many studies have examined how AI affects workers,
 productivity,
 and inequality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These papers often draw on established approaches:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Task-based production models (e.g.,
 Acemoglu & Autor)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Automation and routine-biased technological change
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Human capital and skill-adjustment frameworks
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
While extremely useful,
 these tools were not originally designed to explain the feature of Generative AI (and LLMs in particular) in mind.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Our paper aims to provide a complementary conceptual framework,
 one tailored to the ways AI can:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Perform certain steps of the workflow autonomously,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Augment human work,
 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Chain multiple steps together and execute them at once.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The goal is to connect these capabilities to how work is organized,
 and ultimately,
 how AI reshapes jobs,
 skills,
 and wages.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
